# The Typography Plugin

When you render content you *didn't* hand-write class-by-class — a blog post from markdown, a CMS
field, an AI response — you need beautiful defaults for raw HTML. That's the `@tailwindcss/typography`
plugin, and its `prose` class.

## The problem it solves

Tailwind's preflight intentionally strips default styles (headings aren't bold, lists have no
bullets). Great for UI, terrible for an article. `prose` re-adds tasteful, readable typography to a
whole block of generated HTML.

## Enabling and using it

<CodeBlock
	language="css"
	filename="app.css"
	code={`@import 'tailwindcss';
@plugin '@tailwindcss/typography';`}
/>

<CodeBlock
	playground
	filename="prose"
	code={`<article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
  <h1>The art of readable text</h1>
  <p>With <code>prose</code>, this raw HTML gets sensible spacing, heading sizes, and list styling
     automatically — no per-element classes.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Bulleted lists look right</li>
    <li>Links are styled and underlined</li>
  </ul>
  <blockquote>Even blockquotes get the treatment.</blockquote>
</article>`}
/>

## Modifiers

- **Size:** `prose-sm`, `prose-lg`, `prose-xl`.
- **Theme:** `prose-slate`, `prose-zinc`, etc.; **`dark:prose-invert`** for dark mode.
- **Element overrides:** `prose-headings:font-bold`, `prose-a:text-indigo-600`, `prose-img:rounded-xl`.

<CodeBlock
	language="html"
	filename="customised prose"
	code={`<article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none dark:prose-invert
                prose-headings:font-bold
                prose-a:text-indigo-600 hover:prose-a:text-indigo-700
                prose-img:rounded-xl">
  <!-- markdown-rendered HTML -->
</article>`}
/>

<Callout type="tip" title="This course uses it">

Every lesson body you're reading is rendered with a customised `prose` (see `.lesson-prose` in the
project's `layout.css`). The mdsvex markdown becomes HTML, and `prose` makes it readable — exactly
the use case the plugin exists for.

</Callout>

<Callout type="insight" title="`prose` is for content, not for UI — keep the boundary sharp">

A common mistake is wrapping application UI in `prose`, then fighting its opinionated spacing with
overrides everywhere. Draw a firm line: **`prose` is for rendered long-form content** (articles,
docs, markdown); **utilities are for application chrome** (nav, cards, forms). Use `not-prose` to
opt a UI island out of `prose` when content and UI must coexist. Knowing *where a tool stops* is as
important as knowing how to use it.

</Callout>

## Knowledge check

<Quiz
	question="When is `prose` the right tool?"
	options={[
		{ text: 'For styling your nav bar and buttons', correct: false },
		{ text: 'For HTML you render from markdown/CMS where you can’t add per-element classes', correct: true },
		{ text: 'For making a CSS grid', correct: false },
		{ text: 'Only in dark mode', correct: false }
	]}
	explanation="prose gives readable defaults to generated long-form HTML; use utilities for app UI."
/>

## Recap

- `@plugin '@tailwindcss/typography'` then `prose` styles whole blocks of generated HTML.
- Modify with size (`prose-lg`), theme (`dark:prose-invert`), and element targets (`prose-a:`).
- Keep the boundary: **`prose` for content, utilities for UI**; `not-prose` to opt out.
